  "prompt": "What are some less fictioned movie everyone must watch?",
  "response": "Certainly! Here are some non-fiction and documentary films that are highly acclaimed and informative, covering a range of topics:\n\n1. **13th (2016)** - Directed by Ava DuVernay, this documentary explores the intersection of race, justice, and mass incarceration in the United States.\n\n2. **Won\u2019t You Be My Neighbor? (2018)** - A heartfelt look at the life and legacy of Fred Rogers, host of the beloved children's show \"Mister Rogers' Neighborhood.\"\n\n3. **Jiro Dreams of Sushi (2011)** - A fascinating portrait of Jiro Ono, an 85-year-old sushi master, and his relentless pursuit of perfection in his craft.\n\n4. **The Act of Killing (2012)** - An experimental documentary that challenges former Indonesian death squad leaders to reenact their real-life mass killings in whatever cinematic genres they wish.\n\n5. **My Octopus Teacher (2020)** - This documentary showcases a filmmaker's relationship with an octopus in a South African kelp forest, exploring themes of nature, connection, and personal transformation.\n\n6. **Free Solo (2018)** - A thrilling documentary about rock climber Alex Honnold\u2019s attempt to climb El Capitan in Yosemite National Park without ropes.\n\n7. **The Fog of War (2003)** - An exploration of the complexities of war, featuring former U.S. Secretary of Defense Robert S. McNamara and his reflections on past conflicts.\n\n8. **The Social Dilemma (2020)** - This documentary-drama hybrid examines the dangerous human impact of social networking, with tech experts sounding the alarm on their own creations.\n\n9. **Planet Earth II (2016)** - A stunning sequel to the original documentary series, showcasing the variety of life on the planet and the challenges faced by different species.\n\n10. **Icarus (2017)** - A deep dive into doping in sports, this documentary begins as an investigation into performance-enhancing drugs and unfolds into a major scandal involving Russia's Olympic team.\n\nThese films not only offer entertainment but also provoke thought and insight into important contemporary and historical issues.",
